Text: There's never enough time for anything.
And even though it's only week 2 into the project, I already feel like there's a mountain of things that should be done.
It feels like once you start breaking down a task, there's no ending to it.
Of course, this also means that I've yet to clarified and prioritized my own portion of the project.
And the funny thing is, I almost wish that I was the group communicator this time as I found myself constantly having to ask Bibi to email Eric about something.
Thus, one main goal for next week is to establish a more productive and convenient communication channel for both sides.
Perhaps something like Discord would work, but that probably depends on Eric's and everybody's preference.
Eric's been very responsive, and he even proactively reminds us of hidden quirks in some of the data sets, so I think he wouldn't oppose to the idea.
Another related goal would be to practice prioritizing things from the client's perspective.
Of course, the client can want too many things (like Rodney), but when the client is sure of what he wants, it will be helpful if as a developer I can try to clearly articulate his needs.
For example, as I was wondering about how to send an a price request email from a browser application, I realized that to make everything safe and efficient it's actually a lot of steps.
There are also plenty of options, each with their pros and cons.

While our group will have to settle on one of them eventually, the amount of available options mean that to research them all would be impractical, hence the need to imagine which would most benefit the client.
And of course there's no perfect choice, as each will both lighten or burden the client's workflow in some way.

I also realize that this episode resonates with a message from a random Agile book I'm reading, which states more or less that all that software development is is building something that improves the user's life.
I actually didn't view it that way during the proposal writing stage.
I was more focused on the brief, the elicited requirements, the suitability of this or that technology.
Of course, these forms of conceptualization all derive from that hazy principle of bettering the client's life, but there's always the danger of missing the forest for the trees as well.

Whatever tasks or methods I decide to research about or adopt could make sense technically, but whether they make sense to the user's world is something I will try to deeply reflect on as I pick the next task to work on.
On the practical side, I think that I will propose some changes to our choice of database design, although I'm not sure how much it will deviate from the original proposal.
Basically, given that there are nearly 2000 fields from over 50 files, I can't help feeling that there's a trade-off to be made here.
Even after removing duplicates, there are still about 750 fields (column names) left.

Of course, they can be further reduced due to some being different ways of paraphrasing the same field ('address' and 'company_address'), but I doubt that that would allow the number of columns to drop to a manageable threshold.
Hopefully, I will be able to resolve this issue with my team members and Eric to come up with some balanced solution that would make it easier for all parties (Eric, us, and Eric's clients).
And by 'balance' I mean some agreed and precise constraints on what the database should and should not contain, and what access patterns it should serve.
While generally speaking the app can work with some basic columns, Eric desires to keep as much information just in case and wants to automate updates as well.
But if the data sets don't really have much in common apart from some fundamental columns, then I strongly think a compromise needs to be made.
This compromise could take the shape of using noSQL, for example.
But no matter what, I will try to consider the various needs that the database and application have to serve.
